    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, paying more than the minimum each month will indeed help you hit the principal harder and pay off your loan faster. It's like giving the goblin less gold to keep for himself, so he has less to hoard.\n\nAs for other \"hidden\" ways the interest can catch up to you, the most significant one is if you let the interest compound. With student loans, interest is typically added to the principal balance at the end of each month, which means that the interest for the next month is calculated on a slightly higher balance. This compounding effect can make it seem like the interest is catching up to you.\n\nTo avoid this, you can try making extra payments directly to the principal, which will reduce the balance before the interest is added. This is like giving the goblin a smaller pile of gold to start with, so he has less to take from you.\n\nAnother way to minimize the impact of interest is to pay off your loan as soon as possible. The longer you have the loan, the more interest you'll pay over time. It's like trying to catch a mischievous goblin before it has a chance to hide its gold away.\n\nRemember, the key to paying off your student loan faster is to pay more than the minimum",
